A pulsating eruptive column on 17 April 2010 reached above 8 km altitude, and lightning was frequently seen within the plume.
JMA 2013 catalog says VEI 5. Previously entered as 4? due to conflicting volume reports.
JMA determined this was a VEI 2.
Photos taken on 27 October showed ash deposits on the cone and a small cinder cone growing in the crater.
Based on pilot observations, the Tokyo VAAC reported that on 15 May an ash plume from Aso rose to an altitude of 2.1 km (7,000 ft) a.s.l. and drifted NE.

According to news articles, at least three people were killed and 1,000-2,600 more from several villages were displaced by lahars from Gamalama during 27-28 December. The lahars destroyed many homes in the Tubo and Tofure villages and along the Togorara and Marikurubu rivers.
Observers watching the volcano from 15-22 June reported that a new bocca vent, about 20 m in diameter, had formed at the base of the NE wall of the active crater containing a thermal acid lake.
Venting came from four tephra cones in the main crater/caldera surrounded by meltwater.
Volcanic âbombsâ with cores of white and porous pumice-like material encased in a fine coating of basaltic glass.
Three craters along the S and SE edge of the caldera, with diameters of 200, 300, and 500 m.
Scientists aboard an overflight on 26 October observed lahars in Rio Huemul, to the W.

At 1908 on 25 October an M 4.6 volcano-tectonic earthquake occurred at a depth of 19 km, followed by a seismic swarm starting at 2149. More than 100 events, with depths ranging from 15 to 25 km, were recorded through the next day; 12 of the events were M 3, and three events were M 4.
Scientists aboard an overflight on 26 October observed a white plume with some ash content that rose 1.5 km.
During an overflight by INGEOMINAS on 14 January 2012 it was noted that the higher region of the dome had distinguishable spines that may have formed recently.
Multiple pyroclastic flows about 1.5-2.3 km long destroyed a bridge, damaged a house, and trapped 31 people (later rescued) between the flow paths.
Thermal anomalies on the E flank on 1 June 2012 suggested a pyroclastic flow.

On 28 January, a small lava dome 200 m in diameter appeared on the crater floor near the vent. In three days, it grew to ~600 m in diameter and attained a volume of more than 107 m3. ALOS satellite images disclosed that the dome grew to the point where it completely covered the active vent.

During an overflight on 29 January 2011, scientists from the ERI observed freshly erupted dome material on the crater floor and saw that the crater lake was gone. Fresh pyroclastic flow deposits in the SW crater had runout distances of 500-600 m.
Pumice from this eruption was composed of pyroxene-bearing andesite (57 to 62% SiO2), showing mingling of two magmas with different colors.
Car windows, solar panels, and roofs were damaged from a shockwave and rock fragments that ranged from lapilli to bombs (up to 0.7 m).
The largest explosion, at 0754 on 1 February 2011, launched large blocks and juvenile material that impacted the forest to distances of 3.2 km from the crater.

Roofs were damaged when volcanic bombs traveled up to 16 km NE; JMA reported that strong winds that day contributed to these long dispersal distances. According to local news reports, bombs struck and damaged cars parked in the service area of Miyazaki Expressway and they shattered windows in Kobayashi, 13 km NE.
Ballistics impacted the local region as far as 1 km W and N; ash was reported 60 km E, and lapilli reached 9 km from the crater, damaging solar heaters and roof panels in the town of Takaharu.
Lava flowed down both the W and E sides of the volcano, leaving deep scars on both flanks.
A phreatic eruption from Tompaluan crater was possibly triggered by high rainfall. It produced an ash plume that rose 400 m.

Triyono, a ground post observer, reported "...coals of fire on top of Mount Merapi was caught on camera closed circuit television (CCTV) ... on March 25, starting at 19:40 until March 26 in the morning."

The major highway between Magelang and Yogyakarta was cut off when a 60 m wide section of blacktop was torn away by torrential mudflows. As a result, hundreds of homes within 12 different villages near the river were inundated forcing 5,000 people to flee. There were three fatalities.
No one was killed after a flood of volcanic material from Mount Merapi buried 21 houses in Sleman.
The eruption plume initially rose to altitudes of 9.1-13.7 km; it was detected at altitudes of 6.1-10.7 km during 13-14 June.
Significant ash plumes continued through 19 June.
When ash clouds cleared on 19 June 2011 there was a 15-km-long lava flow already in place extending NW.
On 30 May a small effusive eruption occurred for about two hours.
A NOAA research vessel reported incandescence at the summit at night.
Gas emissions and possible ash. Also on 1-3, 12-13, and 19 July, and 1 September.
Trace amounts of ashfall on parts of the island.
A pilot observed a plume containing a small amount of ash that rose to an altitude below 1.5 km.
Pilots report light ash in gas plumes.
MODVOLC alerts on 6 August, 31 October, 19 November, and 3 and 11 December.
10-20 cm deposit within the 3-km exclusion zone.
Local people observed the dome growing next to the Rokatenda crater in late October.
On 31 August 2011, OVSICORI-UNA reported that since mid-July incandescence was visible during the day on the lava dome of PoÃ¡s, which had not occurred since 1981.
On 20 June scientists observed a viscous lava flow with concentric morphology, confirming speculation of magma ascent reflected in seismic data from the previous few days.
Sailors who went to the crater rim observed a small active vent at the bottom of the Lofia crater. Ledges were also draped with ash.

Swiss adventurer Xavier Rosset posted an audio dialog on 13 March 2009 referring to his visit the preceding week, although the exact date of observation was unclear. The crater was 80-100 m deep and the same in diameter. Three openings of undetermined size displayed an orange glow. Lava ejections from these vents rose 10-50 m high accompanied by loud noises. Rosset's 27 March dialog discusses a strong earthquake in the region on 20 March, which caused several rockfalls on the island. He visited the volcano in the afternoon and, looking into the active crater, saw few noticeable changes.

Nicole Keller: "The only fumaroles were located inside Lofia crater. Every few minutes there was a rumbling, and every now and again (1-2/hour) there was a bigger explosion ejecting juvenile scoria over the crater rim."
Richard Crowley visited and reported seeing lava bubbling in a crater vent.
Ashfall, 4 cm thick, was reported in Krasny Yar (60 km NNW).
Two fissures along the W side of Tolbachinsky Dol.
At least 2 initial cones; 5 by mid-December.

The explosion ejected blocks of lava up to 2 km from the Te Maari Craters area. All blocks were angular, and none were steaming or surrounded by burnt vegetation; GeoNet thus concluded that the blocks comprised old (non-juvenile) lava(s).
A 2- to 5-cm-thick layer of freshly ejected material, with clasts ranging in size from a few millimeters to 5 cm, blanketed the W edge of the crater.
An episode of stronger tremor ended in a volcanic earthquake at 0454 on 5 August. Webcam images revealed an accompanying plume from the crater lake.
Lava emitted from the saddle between the two cones of the Southeast Crater.
Amarillo Ignimbrite may be associated with summit caldera formation
Ship was covered with "cinders from the fire."

Heavy rain on 18 February caused lahars in Ngobo, Mangli (Kediri, 35 km WNW), Bladak (Blitar, 20 km SW), and Konto (Malang, 35 km E). BNPB noted that the lahars flooded five houses and one mosque, and destroyed two homes and one bridge.
